  notes discuss", "the cluster covers", "this knowledge base entry". Start
  with content, not framing.
- Question-implied structure. Every sentence should plausibly answer a
  reader question: what is the core idea, what are the supporting
  concepts, how do they connect, what conclusions or open questions are
  recorded.
- Preserve canonical entity names, technical terms, citations, dates, and
  any explicit conclusions or claims verbatim when they fit naturally.
- 130 to 180 words. Hard floor 100, hard ceiling 220.
- Single block of prose. No headings, no bullets, no markdown.

Return only the description. No preamble, no commentary, no code fences.

